  "prompt": "What is a pantograph? What is it used for?",
  "response": "A pantograph is a mechanical linkage connected in a special way that allows the tracing of a pattern at a different scale. It consists of several connected pivoting arms that can copy or scale a drawing, design, or image. \n\nSome common uses of pantographs include:\n1. Drawing and copying maps at different scales\n2. Engraving and reproducing artwork\n3. Tracing and scaling technical drawings\n4. Copying machine parts or mechanical designs\n5. Woodworking and metalworking to create precise scaled replicas\n6. Historically used by cartographers to create maps\n\nIn electric train and trolley systems, a pantograph is also a device mounted on the roof of a vehicle that connects to overhead electrical lines to collect power for the vehicle's electric motor.",
